        <div class="col-lg-10 col-md-9">
            <h1>iPhone</h1>
            <p>
                The iPhone (commonly known as the "iPhone 2G") was Apple's first smartphone.
                It was announced on {{{date "2007-01-09"}}} and released on {{{date "2007-06-29"}}}.
            </p>

            <h3 id="headingName">Name</h3>
            <p>
                When announced and released, the iPhone 2G was simply called <span class="font-italic">iPhone</span>.
                However, with the release of the {{#link "/devices/iphone/3g"}}iPhone 3G{{/link}} in 2008, the original iPhone became commonly known as the "iPhone <span class="font-italic">2G</span>."
                The reasoning for "2G" and not "1G" is two-fold: it is the iPhone preceding the 3G (and 2 is one before 3), and it only supported {{#link "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GSM"}}GSM{{/link}} and {{#link "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enhanced_Data_Rates_for_GSM_Evolution"}}EDGE{{/link}} networks (commonly called "2G" networks).
            </p>

            <h3 id="headingSpecs">Technical Specs</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Battery: 1400&nbsp;mA @ 3.7&nbsp;V (5.18&nbsp;Wh)</li>
                <li>Bluetooth: 2.0 EDR</li>
                <li>
                    Camera:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Rear: 1.9&nbsp;MP</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Cellular Radio:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Processor: {{#link "/baseband/pmb8876"}}PMB8876{{/link}} (S-Gold 2)</li>
                        <li>Supported networks: Up to EDGE (2.5G)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Colors: Aluminum (gray)</li>
                <li>
                    CPU:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Core: {{#link "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARM11"}}ARM1176{{/link}}&nbsp;x&nbsp;1</li>
                        <li>CPU: {{#link "/processors/s5l8900"}}S5L8900{{/link}}</li>
                        <li>Speed: 412&nbsp;MHz (400 until iPhone OS 1.1.2)</li>
                        <li>Instruction Set: ARMv6</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Firmware:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Initial: {{#link "/fw/keys/1A543a/iphone11"}}1.0 (<code>1A543a</code>){{/link}}</li>
                        <li>Latest: {{#link "/fw/keys/7E18/iphone11"}}3.1.3 (<code>7E18</code>){{/link}}</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Internal Name: <code>iPhone1,1</code></li>
                <li>RAM: 128&nbsp;MiB</li>
                <li>Storage: 4/8/16&nbsp;GB</li>
                <li>Wi-Fi: 802.11b/g</li>
            </ul>

            <h3 id="headingHacking">Hacking</h3>
            <p>
                Naturally, as a first generation device, the original iPhone is one of the more "hack-friendly" {{#link "/devices"}}iDevices{{/link}}.
                Within two months of its release, "{{#link "https://www.theiphonewiki.com/wiki/User:Geohot"}}geohot{{/link}}" (George Hotz) "unlocked" the AT&amp;T only device to {{#link "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvJ1RGlxe8Q"}}work on T-Mobile{{/link}}.
                A few months later, the {{#link "https://www.theiphonewiki.com/wiki/IPhone_Dev_Team"}}iPhone Dev Team{{/link}} discovered "{{#link "https://www.theiphonewiki.com/wiki/Pwnage"}}Pwnage{{/link}}," a bootrom level exploit allowing jailbreaking the device on <em>any</em> version of {{#link "/ios"}}iPhone OS{{/link}}.
            </p>
